  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 3e1cd92da80c7495a8fe7eb91fa80c2f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Bamboo
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Plants.PlantData
  displayName: Bamboo
  audioClip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 288a39f1324be4843988867d2449a118, type: 3}
  environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  poem:
    text: "In Wuqian, Visit a Buddhist Monk's Green Bamboo Pavillion\n\nOne may do
      without meat in one\u2019s diet, \nBut one cannot live without bamboo. \nWithout
      meat, one grows thin; \nWithout bamboo, one grows vulgar. \nA thin man may
      regain his weight, \nBut a vulgar man cannot be cured. \nOthers may laugh at
      these words, \nFinding them both lofty and foolish. \nIf, in the presence of
      this gentleman, one still feasts heartily, \nHow could there ever be a Yangzhou
      Crane in this world?\n\n\u2014 Su Dongpo"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  contextInfos:
  - text: '## Bamboo, The Gentleman


      In Chinese literati tradition, bamboo
      is held as a model of a gentleman: the stem grows straight and does not break
      under pressure, yet the leaves hang loose, almost bowing. It does not bloom,
      symbolising modesty, and its core is hollow, like it''s kepping an open heart.'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: "## The Shijing (Book of Poetry)\n\u77BB\u5F7C\u6DC7\u5967\u3001\u7DA0\u7AF9\u7317\u7317\u3002\n\u6709\u532A\u541B\u5B50\u3001\u5982\u5207\u5982\u78CB\u3001\u5982\u7422\u5982\u78E8\u3002\n\u745F\u516E\u50E9\u516E\u3001\u8D6B\u516E\u54BA\u516E\u3002\n\u6709\u532A\u541B\u5B50\u3001\u7D42\u4E0D\u53EF\u8AFC\u516E\u3002\n\nLook
      at those recesses in the banks of the Qi,\nWith their green bamboos, so fresh
      and luxuriant!\nThere is our elegant and accomplished prince, -\nAs from the
      knife and the file,\nAs from the chisel and the polisher!\nHow grave is he
      and dignified!\nHow commanding and distinguished!\nOur elegant and accomplished
      prince, -\nNever can he be forgotten!"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
